    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>James T. Farrell (1904-1979) was an Irish-American novelist, short story writer, journalist, travel writer, poet, and literary critic.  Born and raised in Chicago, Illinois, he attended the University of Chicago and published his first short story in 1929. He is best known for his <emph render="italic">Studs Lonigan</emph> trilogy and for his <emph render="italic">A note on Literary Criticism</emph>, in which he described two types of the American Marxist character. </p><p>Jack Alan Robbins is the editor of <emph render="italic">Granville Hicks in the New masses</emph> (1974) and <emph render="italic">James T. Farrell: Literary Essays 1954-74</emph> (1976), among other works.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The <emph render="bold">Jack Robbins Collection Relating to James T. Farrell</emph> consist of correspondence, memorabilia, and writings.  </p><p><emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> is primarily between Jack Robbins and others, in particulr Kennikat Press, who was publishing an anthology of Farrell's essays of which Robbins was the editor.  <emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> consists mostly of clippings.  <emph render="bold">Writings</emph> contains reprints of pieces by Farrell, and typescript drafts and notes of Farrell's introduction to the anthology.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>Correspondence is arranged chronologically, all other series alphabetically.</p>
    </arrangement>
